    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-03T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-03T21:00:00-05:00" n="706"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d706">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51 Salt Funds/99: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-04T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >April 4, 1932—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 4—3 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I have received a letter from the two chief inspectors of Salt Revenue, dated
                    March 30th, in which they request, under instructions of the Minister of
                    Finance, that the American Government make urgent appropriate representations to
                    the Japanese Government regarding the refusal of the local authorities in
                    Manchuria, assisted by Japanese advisers and backed by Japanese military forces,
                    to respect the rights of the Chinese Government to the revenues of the salt
                    monopoly; the letter points out that the Salt Inspectorate in China had been set
                    up pursuant to agreements whereby its collections were pledged for the service
                    of international loans. The taking over of the Inspectorate offices in Manchuria
                    is characterized as altogether unprecedented, as destroying its functions in
                    Manchuria, as breaking up the integrity of the Salt Inspectorate as a whole.</p>
                <p>Text by mail.<note n="43" xml:id="d706fn43">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_JNT1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
